            "author_association": "MEMBER",
            "body": "I do think this is quite unexpected indeed, and it only happens for signs placed in a specific group, not the global group. To replicate this I had to distinguish the two cases in #25724:\r\n\r\n```c\r\nstatic uint32_t sign_group_get_next_signid(buf_T *buf, const char *group)\r\n{\r\n  uint32_t ns = group ? (uint32_t)nvim_create_namespace(cstr_as_string((char *)group)) : 0;\r\n\r\n  if (group && marktree_lookup_ns(buf->b_marktree, ns, 1, false, NULL).pos.row < 0) {\r\n    return 1;\r\n  }\r\n\r\n  uint32_t id = group ? map_get(uint32_t, uint32_t)(&namespace_sign_ids, ns) : next_sign_id++;\r\n  // Search for the next usable sign identifier\r\n  while (marktree_lookup_ns(buf->b_marktree, ns, id, false, NULL).pos.row >= 0) {\r\n    id = group ? id + 1 : next_sign_id++;\r\n  }\r\n\r\n  return id;\r\n}\r\n```\r\n\r\nThe global sign id is always incremented, a group sign id is only incremented when it is already found in the buffer. As well as the next group sign id is reset to 1 when it is not found in the buffer, the global sign id is unconditionally incremented.\r\n\r\nShould I fix these instead of keeping it bug-for-bug compatible (will need to adjust some oldtests)?",
